WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.442 --> 00:00:03.025
(bright music)

2
00:00:08.580 --> 00:00:12.030
<v Host>Dr. Holt, she is going to be doing some discussion</v>

3
00:00:12.030 --> 00:00:15.270
here on neurology, everything you need to know.

4
00:00:15.270 --> 00:00:16.770
<v ->We're gonna cover a lot of things today.</v>

5
00:00:16.770 --> 00:00:19.770
We're gonna spend most of our time on seizures.

6
00:00:19.770 --> 00:00:21.030
What is the classification?

7
00:00:21.030 --> 00:00:22.410
Let's talk about some meds.

8
00:00:22.410 --> 00:00:26.250
What do we do with that pregnant patient who has epilepsy?

9
00:00:26.250 --> 00:00:28.440
A fair bit on vascular headaches,

10
00:00:28.440 --> 00:00:32.910
and then kind of a whirlwind through MS.

11
00:00:32.910 --> 00:00:35.400
So let's get right into our first question.

12
00:00:35.400 --> 00:00:37.320
65-year-old male patient of yours

13
00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:40.290
presents to the ED having had a seizure in his bedroom

14
00:00:40.290 --> 00:00:42.030
witnessed by his wife.

15
00:00:42.030 --> 00:00:44.340
She heard a cry, fall to the ground,

16
00:00:44.340 --> 00:00:46.020
saw him stiffen and shake all over,

17
00:00:46.020 --> 00:00:48.030
and then become incontinent of urine.

18
00:00:48.030 --> 00:00:50.280
He was not arousable until he had been in the ED

19
00:00:50.280 --> 00:00:51.600
for several minutes.

20
00:00:51.600 --> 00:00:54.630
His seizure would be classified as which type?

21
00:00:54.630 --> 00:00:57.540
Complex partial, generalized tonic-clonic,

22
00:00:57.540 --> 00:00:59.643
grand mal, or myoclonic?

23
00:01:04.950 --> 00:01:07.080
Good, it is generalized tonic-clonic.

24
00:01:07.080 --> 00:01:10.070
The nomenclature has changed completely

25
00:01:10.070 --> 00:01:11.190
in the neurology world,

26
00:01:11.190 --> 00:01:12.810
so I wanted to just point this out.

27
00:01:12.810 --> 00:01:15.420
So that grand mal term is no more.

28
00:01:15.420 --> 00:01:16.620
So what is a seizure?

29
00:01:16.620 --> 00:01:18.240
It's a transient occurrence

30
00:01:18.240 --> 00:01:20.970
that occurs due to abnormal excitation

31
00:01:20.970 --> 00:01:23.280
and synchronous activity within the brain.

32
00:01:23.280 --> 00:01:25.890
It can be focal, it can be generalized.

33
00:01:25.890 --> 00:01:28.770
10% of adults will have a seizure throughout their lifetime.

34
00:01:28.770 --> 00:01:30.270
So it's pretty common.

35
00:01:30.270 --> 00:01:32.970
One-third will have a recurrence within that first year

36
00:01:32.970 --> 00:01:35.010
of their initial seizure.

37
00:01:35.010 --> 00:01:37.320
We used to call all this stuff partial seizures.

38
00:01:37.320 --> 00:01:39.480
Now it's being called focal seizures,

39
00:01:39.480 --> 00:01:41.160
and they're classified as local,

40
00:01:41.160 --> 00:01:43.620
meaning it starts here and stays here.

41
00:01:43.620 --> 00:01:46.890
You can have ipsilateral propagation along the same side.

42
00:01:46.890 --> 00:01:48.690
You can have contralateral propagation

43
00:01:48.690 --> 00:01:50.730
going to the other side of your brain.

44
00:01:50.730 --> 00:01:53.580
It can start here and then become secondarily generalized

45
00:01:53.580 --> 00:01:55.020
throughout the brain.

46
00:01:55.020 --> 00:01:57.330
And then you would say consciousness is impaired

47
00:01:57.330 --> 00:01:58.380
or not impaired.

48
00:01:58.380 --> 00:02:01.410
We no longer use that complex versus simple.

49
00:02:01.410 --> 00:02:03.660
So literally, every term that could have been changed

50
00:02:03.660 --> 00:02:05.070
in neurology, they've changed 'em all up,

51
00:02:05.070 --> 00:02:06.900
keepin' it exciting.

52
00:02:06.900 --> 00:02:09.360
When we think of these generalized seizures,

53
00:02:09.360 --> 00:02:11.310
non-convulsive or absence

54
00:02:11.310 --> 00:02:13.770
is the one that I'm afraid some of you might be having now.

55
00:02:13.770 --> 00:02:15.688
I'm gonna keep an eye on you.
(audience laughing)

56
00:02:15.688 --> 00:02:17.400
You're staring, you're blinking.

57
00:02:17.400 --> 00:02:18.233
I'm a little worried.

58
00:02:18.233 --> 00:02:21.060
We might have some Depakote at the break if we need it.

59
00:02:21.060 --> 00:02:23.010
So typical absence seizure,

60
00:02:23.010 --> 00:02:25.920
those three-per-second spikes on the EEG.

61
00:02:25.920 --> 00:02:27.960
Atypical is not three per second.

62
00:02:27.960 --> 00:02:29.580
It's less than that.

63
00:02:29.580 --> 00:02:32.130
But EEG, very important for this one.

64
00:02:32.130 --> 00:02:33.090
Convulsive types,

65
00:02:33.090 --> 00:02:35.670
you see all the different classifications up there.

66
00:02:35.670 --> 00:02:36.900
They can be a little tricky

67
00:02:36.900 --> 00:02:38.730
kinda memorizing which is which.

68
00:02:38.730 --> 00:02:40.140
But there they are.

69
00:02:40.140 --> 00:02:43.200
Atonic attacks are worth kind of calling out

70
00:02:43.200 --> 00:02:46.110
because those cause a complete loss of muscle tone

71
00:02:46.110 --> 00:02:48.870
and they have really high rates of injury with them.

72
00:02:48.870 --> 00:02:50.100
They're just walking along fine,

73
00:02:50.100 --> 00:02:51.510
and then, bam, they're down.

74
00:02:51.510 --> 00:02:53.970
So that's kind of a one to be aware of.

75
00:02:53.970 --> 00:02:56.100
PNES has also changed names.

76
00:02:56.100 --> 00:02:58.530
We might remember it as pseudoseizures.

77
00:02:58.530 --> 00:03:01.650
It is now psychogenic non-epileptic seizure.

78
00:03:01.650 --> 00:03:04.083
So again, changing everything that they can.

79
00:03:06.150 --> 00:03:08.670
What would be the most likely cause of a new seizure

80
00:03:08.670 --> 00:03:10.920
in a patient over the age of 65?

81
00:03:10.920 --> 00:03:14.220
CVA or stroke, idiopathic,

82
00:03:14.220 --> 00:03:16.983
metabolic derangement or a brain tumor.

83
00:03:22.560 --> 00:03:23.610
Okay, this is good.

84
00:03:23.610 --> 00:03:26.430
You just squeaked it out, but only 40% or so of you.

85
00:03:26.430 --> 00:03:28.980
So we're gonna talk about why this is the case.

86
00:03:28.980 --> 00:03:31.020
So CVA and stroke is the most common.

87
00:03:31.020 --> 00:03:33.180
If I said for all comers,

88
00:03:33.180 --> 00:03:35.010
those idiopathics would've had it right.

89
00:03:35.010 --> 00:03:38.760
So for all comers, 62% at all ages, idiopathic.

90
00:03:38.760 --> 00:03:40.020
We never find an answer,

91
00:03:40.020 --> 00:03:42.600
which is very frustrating for you as a clinician

92
00:03:42.600 --> 00:03:44.010
and very frustrating for the patients

93
00:03:44.010 --> 00:03:45.310
who are dealing with this.

94
00:03:46.200 --> 00:03:48.540
Stroke is only 15% overall,

95
00:03:48.540 --> 00:03:51.810
but it's 49% for those over the age of 60.

96
00:03:51.810 --> 00:03:54.240
And likewise, brain tumor, about 6% overall.

97
00:03:54.240 --> 00:03:56.610
Goes up to 11% over the age of 60.

98
00:03:56.610 --> 00:03:58.170
So I remember this 60,

99
00:03:58.170 --> 00:04:01.520
60% badness over the age of 60.

100
00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:03.120
Okay, so that's important.

101
00:04:03.120 --> 00:04:04.920
Head trauma, obviously your history's

102
00:04:04.920 --> 00:04:05.790
gonna give you some of that.

103
00:04:05.790 --> 00:04:08.490
Intracranial infections are gonna be important here.

104
00:04:08.490 --> 00:04:11.400
COVID has crept into this lecture as well.

105
00:04:11.400 --> 00:04:15.450
We're seeing 55% more seizures in the first six months

106
00:04:15.450 --> 00:04:18.540
after having COVID versus those who had influenza

107
00:04:18.540 --> 00:04:20.040
in that six-month period.

108
00:04:20.040 --> 00:04:21.007
So it's not just, like,

109
00:04:21.007 --> 00:04:22.830
"Oh, you had an infection and had a fever.

110
00:04:22.830 --> 00:04:24.030
That's what caused it."

111
00:04:24.030 --> 00:04:26.160
There's something different about COVID.

112
00:04:26.160 --> 00:04:27.600
I think we've already figured that out, right.

113
00:04:27.600 --> 00:04:29.310
It's a bizarre one.

114
00:04:29.310 --> 00:04:31.590
In kids, that association is even stronger.

115
00:04:31.590 --> 00:04:33.600
So be aware of that.

116
00:04:33.600 --> 00:04:35.220
Congenital brain malformations,

117
00:04:35.220 --> 00:04:36.870
you're usually gonna have plenty of other signs

118
00:04:36.870 --> 00:04:38.040
before a seizure.

119
00:04:38.040 --> 00:04:40.920
Inborn errors of metabolism, similarly.

120
00:04:40.920 --> 00:04:42.540
What is a provoked seizure?

121
00:04:42.540 --> 00:04:44.910
It means there's a specific thing that happened

122
00:04:44.910 --> 00:04:47.310
that, presumably, if you took that away,

123
00:04:47.310 --> 00:04:49.350
you wouldn't have another seizure.

124
00:04:49.350 --> 00:04:52.020
Hypoglycemia is kind of the hot one on this list,

125
00:04:52.020 --> 00:04:53.340
very common.

126
00:04:53.340 --> 00:04:56.250
Hyponatremia, particularly if you got there quickly,

127
00:04:56.250 --> 00:04:58.140
not if it was a really slow progression

128
00:04:58.140 --> 00:04:59.880
but more of a sudden drop.

129
00:04:59.880 --> 00:05:03.300
For neonates, hypocalcemia is a really big source

130
00:05:03.300 --> 00:05:05.640
of a provoked seizure.

131
00:05:05.640 --> 00:05:07.170
Renal failure and uremia,

132
00:05:07.170 --> 00:05:09.120
again, really sudden people would get there,

133
00:05:09.120 --> 00:05:11.340
not people who've been solely progressing over years.

134
00:05:11.340 --> 00:05:12.173
It's pretty rare.

135
00:05:12.173 --> 00:05:14.160
But if you have a sudden progression to uremia,

136
00:05:14.160 --> 00:05:15.363
that is a high risk.

137
00:05:16.290 --> 00:05:17.640
More rare causes here.

138
00:05:17.640 --> 00:05:20.160
I just like to throw acute intermittent porphyria here

139
00:05:20.160 --> 00:05:22.260
because it seems to be on the differential diagnosis

140
00:05:22.260 --> 00:05:23.400
of everything.

141
00:05:23.400 --> 00:05:25.560
But what's more common in adolescents,

142
00:05:25.560 --> 00:05:28.590
we see this syncope with brief hypoventilation.

143
00:05:28.590 --> 00:05:30.990
This is the classic you'll see on the boards.

144
00:05:30.990 --> 00:05:32.790
The kid is at a choir concert,

145
00:05:32.790 --> 00:05:35.400
and they fall down and have some shaking on the ground.

146
00:05:35.400 --> 00:05:38.370
That's a hypoventilation-induced seizure.

147
00:05:38.370 --> 00:05:41.010
And certainly we see it with alcohol and benzo use

148
00:05:41.010 --> 00:05:42.603
as well as withdrawal.

149
00:05:43.770 --> 00:05:46.470
Epilepsy, if you wanna make a neurologist crazy,

150
00:05:46.470 --> 00:05:49.590
just tell them you have a patient with seizure disorder.

151
00:05:49.590 --> 00:05:50.730
They hate that.

152
00:05:50.730 --> 00:05:53.640
If they've had more than one seizure that wasn't provoked,

153
00:05:53.640 --> 00:05:54.750
they have epilepsy.

154
00:05:54.750 --> 00:05:57.600
They don't want us to use the term seizure disorder.

155
00:05:57.600 --> 00:06:00.660
So two unprovoked seizures at least 24 hours apart,

156
00:06:00.660 --> 00:06:02.130
you have epilepsy.

157
00:06:02.130 --> 00:06:03.900
I think we're afraid to say that sometimes,

158
00:06:03.900 --> 00:06:05.000
but that's what it is.

159
00:06:05.970 --> 00:06:08.190
A patient with a new onset seizure

160
00:06:08.190 --> 00:06:10.830
has a complete workup that is unremarkable

161
00:06:10.830 --> 00:06:13.500
for any provoked causes, signs of infection,

162
00:06:13.500 --> 00:06:16.140
drug toxicities, or neurologic disease.

163
00:06:16.140 --> 00:06:18.210
What is the next step in workup?

164
00:06:18.210 --> 00:06:20.910
Event monitor, prolactin level,

165
00:06:20.910 --> 00:06:23.223
neuroimaging, or lumbar puncture.

166
00:06:28.110 --> 00:06:30.720
Okay, so we have a lot for neuroimaging,

167
00:06:30.720 --> 00:06:33.600
a lot for event monitor, but it is neuroimaging.

168
00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:35.040
That is the next best test.

169
00:06:35.040 --> 00:06:36.330
So let's talk through this.

170
00:06:36.330 --> 00:06:37.890
As with everything else in medicine,

171
00:06:37.890 --> 00:06:39.840
you wanna start with your history and physical

172
00:06:39.840 --> 00:06:40.920
'cause that's who we are, right?

173
00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:42.180
We're clinicians.

174
00:06:42.180 --> 00:06:43.560
If somebody witnessed the event,

175
00:06:43.560 --> 00:06:45.780
that's super helpful for you to know.

176
00:06:45.780 --> 00:06:48.750
Did it start on one side and generalize somewhere else?

177
00:06:48.750 --> 00:06:51.180
If you can find someone who saw it from the beginning,

178
00:06:51.180 --> 00:06:52.740
that's really gonna give you great insight

179
00:06:52.740 --> 00:06:55.260
to the type of seizure that it was.

180
00:06:55.260 --> 00:06:57.540
Is there any substance use disorder history?

181
00:06:57.540 --> 00:06:59.340
Was there a trauma history?

182
00:06:59.340 --> 00:07:00.930
Do they have a history of heart disease?

183
00:07:00.930 --> 00:07:02.670
Do they have any arrhythmias at baseline?

184
00:07:02.670 --> 00:07:04.740
Have they had strokes before?

185
00:07:04.740 --> 00:07:07.470
Sleep disorders is an important one.

186
00:07:07.470 --> 00:07:08.647
Sometimes people will say, like,

187
00:07:08.647 --> 00:07:10.110
"Oh, my husband has, you know,

188
00:07:10.110 --> 00:07:11.430
a seizure every night before bed.

189
00:07:11.430 --> 00:07:12.990
He kinda like goes like this."

190
00:07:12.990 --> 00:07:14.790
Those are hypnagogic twitches.

191
00:07:14.790 --> 00:07:15.750
Those are not seizures.

192
00:07:15.750 --> 00:07:18.390
So that's great history to kinda dig through.

193
00:07:18.390 --> 00:07:21.210
Insomnia, patients who really struggle with insomnia

194
00:07:21.210 --> 00:07:22.350
do have more seizures

195
00:07:22.350 --> 00:07:24.420
because it lowers the seizure threshold.

196
00:07:24.420 --> 00:07:25.830
And there are certain seizures

197
00:07:25.830 --> 00:07:27.690
that increase frequency at bedtime

198
00:07:27.690 --> 00:07:29.550
and are actually more fatal because of that.

199
00:07:29.550 --> 00:07:32.043
So get into that sleep history a bit.

200
00:07:33.120 --> 00:07:35.190
This is a really important slide.

201
00:07:35.190 --> 00:07:37.500
There are many medications that patients are on

202
00:07:37.500 --> 00:07:39.510
that can lower that seizure threshold.

203
00:07:39.510 --> 00:07:42.360
So if you have somebody with the first onset of seizure,

204
00:07:42.360 --> 00:07:44.760
you really wanna dig into their med list.

205
00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:46.710
The ones that I'll call out in particular,

206
00:07:46.710 --> 00:07:49.140
tramadol and Wellbutrin.

207
00:07:49.140 --> 00:07:50.820
Those are kinda the two hot players

208
00:07:50.820 --> 00:07:52.050
that you see a lot on boards,

209
00:07:52.050 --> 00:07:54.030
and it's also important in real life.

210
00:07:54.030 --> 00:07:55.650
But look at that antihistamine.

211
00:07:55.650 --> 00:07:57.750
That one came as a surprise to me.

212
00:07:57.750 --> 00:08:00.030
They've done a fair bit of studies on this now.

213
00:08:00.030 --> 00:08:02.280
Histamine levels are kind of important.

214
00:08:02.280 --> 00:08:05.580
If you have lower histamine levels by taking antihistamines,

215
00:08:05.580 --> 00:08:07.140
you lower your seizure threshold.

216
00:08:07.140 --> 00:08:10.350
You have more seizures and seizures of longer duration.

217
00:08:10.350 --> 00:08:12.930
So this was a knowledge deficit for me a few years back.

218
00:08:12.930 --> 00:08:15.000
I had one of my patients with epilepsy

219
00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:16.950
who was taking over-the-counter antihistamines

220
00:08:16.950 --> 00:08:18.510
'cause I didn't tell her not to.

221
00:08:18.510 --> 00:08:20.040
She ended up with a pretty big seizure

222
00:08:20.040 --> 00:08:21.870
that lasted a long time in the ER.

223
00:08:21.870 --> 00:08:23.970
So now that's a part of my routine talk.

224
00:08:23.970 --> 00:08:25.230
If anyone's ever had a seizure,

225
00:08:25.230 --> 00:08:26.063
I say, "Hey, you know what?

226
00:08:26.063 --> 00:08:27.510
You can't take over the counter Benadryl,

227
00:08:27.510 --> 00:08:28.810
and let's talk about why."

228
00:08:30.420 --> 00:08:33.120
Basic evaluation for everybody are some basic labs.

229
00:08:33.120 --> 00:08:34.410
You don't need to get crazy here.

230
00:08:34.410 --> 00:08:36.570
But basic things really are important for everybody.

231
00:08:36.570 --> 00:08:40.380
So CBC, electrolytes, including calc, mag and phos,

232
00:08:40.380 --> 00:08:42.213
glucose and some renal function.

233
00:08:43.230 --> 00:08:45.240
ESR, LFTs, RPR,

234
00:08:45.240 --> 00:08:48.210
only if my history is pointing me in that direction, okay?

235
00:08:48.210 --> 00:08:50.490
And prolactin, just throw that away.

236
00:08:50.490 --> 00:08:52.177
We used to think that was a really great test.

237
00:08:52.177 --> 00:08:53.340
"If the prolactin was up,

238
00:08:53.340 --> 00:08:54.990
oh they really did have a seizure."

239
00:08:54.990 --> 00:08:57.390
Nope, that's been completely and proven to be

240
00:08:57.390 --> 00:08:58.863
very low sensitivity.

241
00:08:59.700 --> 00:09:02.340
Lumbar puncture, only if your history points you there

242
00:09:02.340 --> 00:09:03.750
if there's signs of infection.

243
00:09:03.750 --> 00:09:06.150
But the EEG is important for everybody

244
00:09:06.150 --> 00:09:07.800
'cause there's certain things on an EEG

245
00:09:07.800 --> 00:09:10.740
that will prompt you for different treatment.

246
00:09:10.740 --> 00:09:13.110
Neuroimaging, as we talked about in this question,

247
00:09:13.110 --> 00:09:15.150
is an important part of the workup.

248
00:09:15.150 --> 00:09:17.193
MRI is preferred over a CT,

249
00:09:18.060 --> 00:09:20.040
but as with anything else with MRI,

250
00:09:20.040 --> 00:09:21.360
you might find a bunch of stuff.

251
00:09:21.360 --> 00:09:22.950
Is that the source of the seizure?

252
00:09:22.950 --> 00:09:23.783
We don't know.

253
00:09:23.783 --> 00:09:24.900
It's hard to know if the lesion

254
00:09:24.900 --> 00:09:26.523
is actually causing the problem.

255
00:09:29.670 --> 00:09:31.350
Okay so, patient presents to you having

256
00:09:31.350 --> 00:09:33.510
a single new unprovoked seizure

257
00:09:33.510 --> 00:09:35.790
with a completely negative workup.

258
00:09:35.790 --> 00:09:37.530
Your first step in treatment would be:

259
00:09:37.530 --> 00:09:39.780
start no medications at this time,

260
00:09:39.780 --> 00:09:41.730
start oral valproic acid,

261
00:09:41.730 --> 00:09:45.371
start oral phenytoin, or start some oral Keppra.

262
00:09:45.371 --> 00:09:47.153
What do we wanna do for this patient?

263
00:09:51.870 --> 00:09:52.770
Good job.

264
00:09:52.770 --> 00:09:55.920
So even though Keppra's super popular right now,

265
00:09:55.920 --> 00:09:57.300
starting no meds at this point

266
00:09:57.300 --> 00:09:59.730
is actually the recommended treatment.

267
00:09:59.730 --> 00:10:02.490
So if it's a single seizure, not a recurrent,

268
00:10:02.490 --> 00:10:05.310
but a single seizure or very infrequent seizures,

269
00:10:05.310 --> 00:10:07.353
you can opt for no treatment at all.

270
00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:09.540
If they did some studies

271
00:10:09.540 --> 00:10:11.670
comparing immediate anti-epileptic drugs

272
00:10:11.670 --> 00:10:13.800
to just kinda watchful waiting,

273
00:10:13.800 --> 00:10:16.470
you do decrease your chances of having a next seizure

274
00:10:16.470 --> 00:10:18.870
within two years by starting anti-epileptic drugs.

275
00:10:18.870 --> 00:10:21.000
Well, I hope so. That's what they're there for.

276
00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:24.330
But it does not improve quality of life, okay?

277
00:10:24.330 --> 00:10:26.280
And if you look beyond that two-year window,

278
00:10:26.280 --> 00:10:27.810
if you look at three years and beyond,

279
00:10:27.810 --> 00:10:29.610
there's no difference in amount of seizures,

280
00:10:29.610 --> 00:10:31.770
quality of life, any of that stuff.

281
00:10:31.770 --> 00:10:33.570
So really we wanna look at who are those

282
00:10:33.570 --> 00:10:36.060
high risk seizure patients that might need treatment

283
00:10:36.060 --> 00:10:37.980
even after their first time.

284
00:10:37.980 --> 00:10:39.810
Status epilepticus is one of them.

285
00:10:39.810 --> 00:10:42.960
If you have a single episode of status in the hospital,

286
00:10:42.960 --> 00:10:45.630
you're on lifelong antiepileptic drugs.

287
00:10:45.630 --> 00:10:47.310
If you have a history of a brain injury,

288
00:10:47.310 --> 00:10:50.250
if there is an abnormality on that MRI that you got,

289
00:10:50.250 --> 00:10:53.220
that's probably somebody who warrants treatment.

290
00:10:53.220 --> 00:10:56.280
If you have any focal neurologic abnormalities on exam,

291
00:10:56.280 --> 00:10:57.870
you're gonna treat those people.

292
00:10:57.870 --> 00:11:00.300
If you have a patient with intellectual disability,

293
00:11:00.300 --> 00:11:01.950
treat that person.

294
00:11:01.950 --> 00:11:04.800
And then there are certain high-risk seizure types

295
00:11:04.800 --> 00:11:06.960
that either they're really high risk of recurrence

296
00:11:06.960 --> 00:11:09.150
or really high risk of injury from them,

297
00:11:09.150 --> 00:11:10.710
like we talked out with the atonic

298
00:11:10.710 --> 00:11:13.080
or the nocturnal seizures,

299
00:11:13.080 --> 00:11:13.913
Treat those.

300
00:11:13.913 --> 00:11:15.450
Something just hit from AFP,

301
00:11:15.450 --> 00:11:17.610
the little thing that they email me all the time.

302
00:11:17.610 --> 00:11:21.180
They found a a link with nocturnal seizures and SIDS now.

303
00:11:21.180 --> 00:11:23.463
So, hmm, maybe we'll learn more about that.

304
00:11:24.570 --> 00:11:27.690
If you are gonna start somebody on antiepileptic medication,

305
00:11:27.690 --> 00:11:29.160
you're gonna just do one of them, right?

306
00:11:29.160 --> 00:11:31.353
So monotherapy is really important,

307
00:11:32.220 --> 00:11:35.340
and the selection is based on what type of seizure they had,

308
00:11:35.340 --> 00:11:37.680
what their insurance looks like, what other meds they're on.

309
00:11:37.680 --> 00:11:39.780
There's a lot of factors that you can use.

310
00:11:39.780 --> 00:11:42.120
But it's important to not do any combination therapy

311
00:11:42.120 --> 00:11:45.990
unless they have failed two different monotherapy trials.

312
00:11:45.990 --> 00:11:48.540
And unfortunately, one-third of patients with epilepsy

313
00:11:48.540 --> 00:11:51.630
will be on multiple meds and still have refractory seizures.

314
00:11:51.630 --> 00:11:54.060
So that is important for the patient to realize

315
00:11:54.060 --> 00:11:56.070
that we sometimes can't get you seizure-free

316
00:11:56.070 --> 00:11:57.453
even with a bunch of meds.

317
00:11:59.100 --> 00:12:00.870
Classifications are kind of broken

318
00:12:00.870 --> 00:12:03.480
into broad spectrum and narrow spectrum,

319
00:12:03.480 --> 00:12:04.680
and they're just what they sound like.

320
00:12:04.680 --> 00:12:07.140
Broad spectrum covers a bunch of types of seizures,

321
00:12:07.140 --> 00:12:09.810
whereas narrow spectrum is only for certain.

322
00:12:09.810 --> 00:12:12.090
First generation are older ones, right?

323
00:12:12.090 --> 00:12:13.530
They're less expensive.

324
00:12:13.530 --> 00:12:15.360
So some of our patients have to be on those.

325
00:12:15.360 --> 00:12:17.070
But there are many more drug interactions,

326
00:12:17.070 --> 00:12:20.640
and oftentimes we have to do more monitoring of drug levels.

327
00:12:20.640 --> 00:12:22.770
Second generation agents, easier to take,

328
00:12:22.770 --> 00:12:25.980
no monitoring needed, but the price tag does go up.

329
00:12:25.980 --> 00:12:27.870
Here's some examples of first generation

330
00:12:27.870 --> 00:12:29.133
and second generation.

331
00:12:31.110 --> 00:12:32.460
This I thought was really fascinating.

332
00:12:32.460 --> 00:12:34.890
I guess I assumed there was just excellent data

333
00:12:34.890 --> 00:12:36.750
on, like, "If I have this type of seizure,

334
00:12:36.750 --> 00:12:37.980
this is the type of medicine

335
00:12:37.980 --> 00:12:39.840
that is strength of recommendation A."

336
00:12:39.840 --> 00:12:41.460
You see there's very little of that.

337
00:12:41.460 --> 00:12:43.110
Focal seizures, we're pretty good.

338
00:12:43.110 --> 00:12:45.660
We have a lot of strength of recommendation A.

339
00:12:45.660 --> 00:12:47.010
When you look at generalized,

340
00:12:47.010 --> 00:12:48.900
the only thing that really has a great data

341
00:12:48.900 --> 00:12:52.410
is absence seizures in less than 16-year-olds.

342
00:12:52.410 --> 00:12:55.200
Everybody else is really expert opinion.

343
00:12:55.200 --> 00:12:58.350
And so you just base it on side effect, profile, cost,

344
00:12:58.350 --> 00:12:59.300
that kind of thing.

345
00:13:00.900 --> 00:13:04.590
Toxicities, the boards love medication toxicities.

346
00:13:04.590 --> 00:13:05.670
So if you have somebody

347
00:13:05.670 --> 00:13:07.950
and there's something about a epileptic patient,

348
00:13:07.950 --> 00:13:09.510
blah, blah blah, havin' these weird symptoms,

349
00:13:09.510 --> 00:13:11.940
and if a choice is a medication side effect,

350
00:13:11.940 --> 00:13:13.410
choose that answer.

351
00:13:13.410 --> 00:13:15.240
Antiepileptic drugs have a ton.

352
00:13:15.240 --> 00:13:17.640
31% report adverse effects,

353
00:13:17.640 --> 00:13:19.410
and the adherence to these medications

354
00:13:19.410 --> 00:13:21.480
are very, very low because of that.

355
00:13:21.480 --> 00:13:23.670
Suicidality goes up two times.

356
00:13:23.670 --> 00:13:25.320
And it's not just the epilepsy.

357
00:13:25.320 --> 00:13:27.510
They look at those who are on meds with epilepsy

358
00:13:27.510 --> 00:13:28.350
and those who aren't,

359
00:13:28.350 --> 00:13:31.277
and they have a higher rate of suicidality.

360
00:13:31.277 --> 00:13:34.267
Neurotoxicity, this is the main reason people stop.

361
00:13:34.267 --> 00:13:35.670
"I feel like junk on them.

362
00:13:35.670 --> 00:13:38.550
I have fatigue, I have a headache, I'm dizzy,

363
00:13:38.550 --> 00:13:39.960
I keep falling asleep at work."

364
00:13:39.960 --> 00:13:40.800
All these kinds of things

365
00:13:40.800 --> 00:13:43.530
can be, obvious, a major issue for patients.

366
00:13:43.530 --> 00:13:47.490
The rash, we get really excited about this, and we need to.

367
00:13:47.490 --> 00:13:50.100
You can have anything from a little macular papular rash

368
00:13:50.100 --> 00:13:51.570
all the way to Stevens-Johnson.

369
00:13:51.570 --> 00:13:53.310
So you do need to tell any patient

370
00:13:53.310 --> 00:13:55.237
starting on a anti-epileptic drug,

371
00:13:55.237 --> 00:13:56.910
"If you develop any rash,

372
00:13:56.910 --> 00:13:59.010
I need to see you, like, today in the office

373
00:13:59.010 --> 00:14:00.930
'cause it could be an emergency.

374
00:14:00.930 --> 00:14:02.670
And then liver enzyme induction,

375
00:14:02.670 --> 00:14:04.290
you're always just gonna have to check med lists

376
00:14:04.290 --> 00:14:06.843
if they're on these anti-epileptic drugs.

377
00:14:08.460 --> 00:14:10.440
46-year-old male patient of your practice

378
00:14:10.440 --> 00:14:13.260
presents with fever, arthralgias and erythrodermic.

379
00:14:13.260 --> 00:14:14.610
No respiratory symptoms.

380
00:14:14.610 --> 00:14:16.170
His meds include lisinopril,

381
00:14:16.170 --> 00:14:18.240
valproic acid and atenolol.

382
00:14:18.240 --> 00:14:20.220
Fever of 102.2.

383
00:14:20.220 --> 00:14:23.730
His skin reveals erythematous macular papular rash

384
00:14:23.730 --> 00:14:25.110
with some tenderness.

385
00:14:25.110 --> 00:14:26.790
No oral lesions.

386
00:14:26.790 --> 00:14:30.530
White count is 16,000 with 17% eosinophils.

387
00:14:30.530 --> 00:14:33.420
ALT and AST are twice normal.

388
00:14:33.420 --> 00:14:35.340
What is your most likely diagnosis?

389
00:14:35.340 --> 00:14:38.370
Toxic shock syndrome, DRESS syndrome.

390
00:14:38.370 --> 00:14:40.200
Stephens-Johnson syndrome,

391
00:14:40.200 --> 00:14:43.957
or neurocutaneous phakomatosis syndrome.

392
00:14:47.920 --> 00:14:48.753
Okay, good.

393
00:14:48.753 --> 00:14:50.700
60% of you are DRESS syndrome.

394
00:14:50.700 --> 00:14:53.010
This is growing over the last few years.

395
00:14:53.010 --> 00:14:55.440
First time I put this up, kinda nobody knew what that was.

396
00:14:55.440 --> 00:14:57.180
So we're startin' to hear a little more about this,

397
00:14:57.180 --> 00:14:59.550
and we're gonna find out why that is the case.

398
00:14:59.550 --> 00:15:01.410
If you knew what DRESS syndrome stood for,

399
00:15:01.410 --> 00:15:02.790
you would've gotten it right, for sure,

400
00:15:02.790 --> 00:15:04.920
'cause it just lays it right out there for you.

401
00:15:04.920 --> 00:15:09.000
Drug reaction with eosinophilia and systemic symptoms.

402
00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:10.350
So the rash is common,

403
00:15:10.350 --> 00:15:13.590
fever, arthralgias, lymphadenopathy,

404
00:15:13.590 --> 00:15:15.990
has up to a 25% mortality rate.

405
00:15:15.990 --> 00:15:17.610
That's pretty terrible.

406
00:15:17.610 --> 00:15:19.590
Why the heck are we talking about it now?

407
00:15:19.590 --> 00:15:21.060
Because antiepileptic drugs

408
00:15:21.060 --> 00:15:24.000
are the most common offending agents of this.

409
00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:25.950
You do see a little bit with allopurinol

410
00:15:25.950 --> 00:15:27.090
and sulfonamides as well,

411
00:15:27.090 --> 00:15:30.480
but it's usually due to epilepsy medications.

412
00:15:30.480 --> 00:15:32.940
So we understand there to be some sort of a continuum

413
00:15:32.940 --> 00:15:35.610
between Stevens-Johnson's and DRESS syndrome.

414
00:15:35.610 --> 00:15:37.830
DRESS syndrome, they're not gonna look as bad,

415
00:15:37.830 --> 00:15:40.860
like mucocutaneous, and skin won't look as scary,

416
00:15:40.860 --> 00:15:42.330
but they're actually far sicker.

417
00:15:42.330 --> 00:15:44.550
Their organ dysfunction is actually higher

418
00:15:44.550 --> 00:15:45.870
for DRESS syndrome.

419
00:15:45.870 --> 00:15:47.100
So how do you treat them?

420
00:15:47.100 --> 00:15:49.350
You take them off the med that probably caused it,

421
00:15:49.350 --> 00:15:50.183
and you support them.

422
00:15:50.183 --> 00:15:53.190
There is no other treatment other than supportive care.

423
00:15:53.190 --> 00:15:54.667
But again, tell those patients,

424
00:15:54.667 --> 00:15:56.400
"Call me if you ever get a rash on this."

425
00:15:56.400 --> 00:15:57.250
That's important.

426
00:15:58.380 --> 00:16:00.690
So we talked before that status is a big deal,

427
00:16:00.690 --> 00:16:03.600
and if you have one time you get on meds,

428
00:16:03.600 --> 00:16:04.530
this is what it is.

429
00:16:04.530 --> 00:16:05.850
So it's a single seizure

430
00:16:05.850 --> 00:16:07.650
lasting for more than five minutes,

431
00:16:07.650 --> 00:16:09.060
or it's recurrent seizures

432
00:16:09.060 --> 00:16:11.700
without a return to baseline between them.

433
00:16:11.700 --> 00:16:13.350
Convulsive are the most common,

434
00:16:13.350 --> 00:16:15.000
and it's a generalized convulsive

435
00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:16.920
tonic-clonic kind of seizure.

436
00:16:16.920 --> 00:16:18.720
Non-convulsive ones are tough

437
00:16:18.720 --> 00:16:21.390
'cause they're a little bit harder to tell it's happening.

438
00:16:21.390 --> 00:16:23.340
Refractory are obviously also tough

439
00:16:23.340 --> 00:16:25.440
'cause they're not responding to treatment.

440
00:16:25.440 --> 00:16:27.180
The non-convulsive, though, is important,

441
00:16:27.180 --> 00:16:28.500
and we miss this a lot.

442
00:16:28.500 --> 00:16:30.740
These are typically patients in the ICU

443
00:16:30.740 --> 00:16:32.580
or they're their post-ICU stay,

444
00:16:32.580 --> 00:16:34.470
and they're kinda wandering around confused,

445
00:16:34.470 --> 00:16:36.570
and you just think they've got some delirium.

446
00:16:36.570 --> 00:16:38.940
Or if they're in the unit sedated on event,

447
00:16:38.940 --> 00:16:41.670
make sure you're opening their eyes every day.

448
00:16:41.670 --> 00:16:44.550
That is like the one clue for a non-convulsive status.

449
00:16:44.550 --> 00:16:46.140
You'll just see those eyes goin',

450
00:16:46.140 --> 00:16:48.300
and they're in status, and we're not treating them.

451
00:16:48.300 --> 00:16:50.160
So that's why this one can be really scary

452
00:16:50.160 --> 00:16:51.480
because we miss it.

453
00:16:51.480 --> 00:16:54.120
Mortality rates up to 52% in some studies

454
00:16:54.120 --> 00:16:57.063
for a non convulsive 'cause we just didn't diagnose it.

455
00:16:59.310 --> 00:17:01.020
What do you do to treat this?

456
00:17:01.020 --> 00:17:03.240
Lorazepam, that's kind of our treatment of choice.

457
00:17:03.240 --> 00:17:06.390
If you don't have IV access or IV blue,

458
00:17:06.390 --> 00:17:07.500
we've got IM options.

459
00:17:07.500 --> 00:17:09.120
We've got rectal options.

460
00:17:09.120 --> 00:17:11.460
The whole thing, though, is you just start treating them.

461
00:17:11.460 --> 00:17:12.930
You work it up while you're treating,

462
00:17:12.930 --> 00:17:14.910
but you don't wait to find the reason

463
00:17:14.910 --> 00:17:15.743
to give them treatment.

464
00:17:15.743 --> 00:17:17.490
Just start throwing stuff at them.

465
00:17:17.490 --> 00:17:19.710
Most of the time you will need very urgent control

466
00:17:19.710 --> 00:17:21.690
with an antiepileptic med as well.

467
00:17:21.690 --> 00:17:24.750
So you'll start those right after you start that Ativan.

468
00:17:24.750 --> 00:17:28.110
So fosphenytoin is a common one or phenobarb, valproate,

469
00:17:28.110 --> 00:17:29.760
those are all things you can do IV

470
00:17:29.760 --> 00:17:31.533
to get them loaded very quickly.

471
00:17:33.450 --> 00:17:35.940
So Dr. Weissmuller talked about a guideline,

472
00:17:35.940 --> 00:17:37.440
I think, from 1992.

473
00:17:37.440 --> 00:17:39.840
I've got one from 1994 here

474
00:17:39.840 --> 00:17:43.470
that says if you have a seizure and you're driving,

475
00:17:43.470 --> 00:17:45.810
you should resist driving for three months.

476
00:17:45.810 --> 00:17:48.420
So any seizure, whatever setting it was in,

477
00:17:48.420 --> 00:17:50.250
you should not drive for three months.

478
00:17:50.250 --> 00:17:52.620
The neurologic association said that in '94,

479
00:17:52.620 --> 00:17:55.320
and they've actually stuck by that recommendation.

480
00:17:55.320 --> 00:17:58.530
We do know that MVAs are not that common

481
00:17:58.530 --> 00:17:59.400
because of seizures.

482
00:17:59.400 --> 00:18:02.460
They're way more common from things like alcohol use.

483
00:18:02.460 --> 00:18:05.013
But it is still a recommendation for no driving.

484
00:18:06.090 --> 00:18:08.340
But it's important to know your own state laws.

485
00:18:08.340 --> 00:18:09.173
They're all different.

486
00:18:09.173 --> 00:18:11.750
So wherever you practice, know what those rules are.

487
00:18:12.600 --> 00:18:15.840
Most will prohibit lifetime commercial driving

488
00:18:15.840 --> 00:18:17.970
with even a single episode of a seizure.

489
00:18:17.970 --> 00:18:21.630
So just be aware of what those rules may be where you are.

490
00:18:21.630 --> 00:18:23.490
What about when it comes to contraception?

491
00:18:23.490 --> 00:18:25.170
We know that these meds, as I said,

492
00:18:25.170 --> 00:18:26.730
have a lot of drug interactions,

493
00:18:26.730 --> 00:18:28.500
and they can really mess this up.

494
00:18:28.500 --> 00:18:30.900
So we have seen numerous examples and studies

495
00:18:30.900 --> 00:18:34.500
confirm contraception failure on antiepileptic drugs

496
00:18:34.500 --> 00:18:37.500
that stimulate the cytochrome P450 system.

497
00:18:37.500 --> 00:18:39.150
The ones that don't do this

498
00:18:39.150 --> 00:18:40.680
are your Keppra and your Depakote.

499
00:18:40.680 --> 00:18:42.840
So those would be potentially better options

500
00:18:42.840 --> 00:18:45.363
if a patient needs to be on hormonal treatment.

501
00:18:46.710 --> 00:18:48.480
Antiepileptic drugs also interfere

502
00:18:48.480 --> 00:18:51.360
with progestin-only pills, contraceptive rings,

503
00:18:51.360 --> 00:18:53.040
progestin implants.

504
00:18:53.040 --> 00:18:54.960
They do not seem to be interfering

505
00:18:54.960 --> 00:18:58.200
with Depo or any type of IUD.

506
00:18:58.200 --> 00:19:00.300
So that's gonna be a great option for patients

507
00:19:00.300 --> 00:19:03.990
who have requirements for antiepileptic drugs.

508
00:19:03.990 --> 00:19:07.320
Be aware, too, that particularly with Lamictal, lamotrigine,

509
00:19:07.320 --> 00:19:11.100
oral contraceptives can decrease the level of Lamictal

510
00:19:11.100 --> 00:19:13.473
and increase your rate of having seizures.

511
00:19:14.730 --> 00:19:16.410
What about that patient who has epilepsy

512
00:19:16.410 --> 00:19:17.400
who's getting pregnant?

513
00:19:17.400 --> 00:19:19.290
Well, maybe you have that unicorn patient

514
00:19:19.290 --> 00:19:21.810
who actually comes in for a preconception counseling.

515
00:19:21.810 --> 00:19:23.460
I don't seem to get many of those.

516
00:19:23.460 --> 00:19:25.410
But if they do, you have a conversation.

517
00:19:25.410 --> 00:19:27.390
If they haven't had a seizure in two years,

518
00:19:27.390 --> 00:19:29.190
you would think about weaning them off

519
00:19:29.190 --> 00:19:30.510
of their antiepileptic drug

520
00:19:30.510 --> 00:19:32.790
six months before becoming pregnant.

521
00:19:32.790 --> 00:19:34.200
Most of the time they roll in

522
00:19:34.200 --> 00:19:35.400
after they're already pregnant,

523
00:19:35.400 --> 00:19:37.650
and they're on their antiepileptic drug.

524
00:19:37.650 --> 00:19:38.910
If so, you let it be.

525
00:19:38.910 --> 00:19:41.880
You do not change the medication based on that.

526
00:19:41.880 --> 00:19:43.380
Dr. Weissmuller already pointed out

527
00:19:43.380 --> 00:19:44.550
that if you're on some meds,

528
00:19:44.550 --> 00:19:47.010
you need way more folic acid than usual.

529
00:19:47.010 --> 00:19:49.650
So four milligrams if you're on carbamazepine

530
00:19:49.650 --> 00:19:52.680
or valproic acid because of that neural tube issue.

531
00:19:52.680 --> 00:19:54.300
For all the other antiepileptics,

532
00:19:54.300 --> 00:19:57.663
it's 800 micrograms a day, whereas everybody else is 400.

533
00:19:59.340 --> 00:20:01.320
You're gonna monitor drug levels more frequently

534
00:20:01.320 --> 00:20:02.700
'cause people's weights are changing.

535
00:20:02.700 --> 00:20:05.550
Their fluid status is changing a lot with pregnancy.

536
00:20:05.550 --> 00:20:08.490
There's some recommendations for vitamin K supplementation

537
00:20:08.490 --> 00:20:09.870
that last month of pregnancy

538
00:20:09.870 --> 00:20:12.180
if you're on certain anti-epileptic drugs.

539
00:20:12.180 --> 00:20:14.550
And you are allowed to breastfeed on all of them,

540
00:20:14.550 --> 00:20:15.840
except Lamotrigine.

541
00:20:15.840 --> 00:20:18.813
That would be recommended to not breastfeed with that one.

542
00:20:20.520 --> 00:20:21.840
Okay, we're switching gears here.

543
00:20:21.840 --> 00:20:24.960
46-year-old male smoker comes to you for a complaint

544
00:20:24.960 --> 00:20:27.510
of a unilateral cyclical nocturnal headache

545
00:20:27.510 --> 00:20:29.430
that lasts 30 minutes each.

546
00:20:29.430 --> 00:20:30.900
He's taken over-the-counter meds,

547
00:20:30.900 --> 00:20:32.640
but they have not been helpful.

548
00:20:32.640 --> 00:20:34.440
The best prophylactic medication

549
00:20:34.440 --> 00:20:35.910
for his headaches would be:

550
00:20:35.910 --> 00:20:38.730
oxygen, sumatriptan,

551
00:20:38.730 --> 00:20:41.013
propanolol or verapamil.

552
00:20:42.720 --> 00:20:44.823
How are we gonna prevent his headaches?

553
00:20:50.130 --> 00:20:52.560
Okay, we have some learning opportunity here.

554
00:20:52.560 --> 00:20:55.080
But a little more of you squeaked out verapamil,

555
00:20:55.080 --> 00:20:56.820
which is the answer.

556
00:20:56.820 --> 00:20:59.250
So oxygen people, sumatriptan people,

557
00:20:59.250 --> 00:21:01.290
that would be decent for abortive therapy

558
00:21:01.290 --> 00:21:04.110
but not for preventative therapy.

559
00:21:04.110 --> 00:21:05.430
So what are we gonna hit today?

560
00:21:05.430 --> 00:21:07.770
Primary headaches, and obviously headaches could be,

561
00:21:07.770 --> 00:21:10.560
like, a multi-day conference all by itself.

562
00:21:10.560 --> 00:21:12.210
I'm gonna hit kind of three major types,

563
00:21:12.210 --> 00:21:15.390
tension types, trigeminal types and migraine.

564
00:21:15.390 --> 00:21:16.380
There's lots of others,

565
00:21:16.380 --> 00:21:18.600
and we're not gonna touch on them at all.

566
00:21:18.600 --> 00:21:20.310
For the chronic tension headaches,

567
00:21:20.310 --> 00:21:21.600
these are band-like, right?

568
00:21:21.600 --> 00:21:24.150
Your head feels like it's in a vice kind of thing.

569
00:21:24.150 --> 00:21:27.150
Treatment is over-the-counter analgesics to start with.

570
00:21:27.150 --> 00:21:29.910
If you're using those more than twice a week, though,

571
00:21:29.910 --> 00:21:31.770
you do increase the risk of progressing

572
00:21:31.770 --> 00:21:33.420
to chronic daily headache.

573
00:21:33.420 --> 00:21:36.457
So if so, think about those TCAs, amitriptyline.

574
00:21:36.457 --> 00:21:39.210
Elavil is a great choice for prevention of these,

575
00:21:39.210 --> 00:21:41.640
and that's strength of recommendation B

576
00:21:41.640 --> 00:21:44.760
Butalbital, opioids, not recommended for these.

577
00:21:44.760 --> 00:21:46.050
They have a much higher chance

578
00:21:46.050 --> 00:21:48.630
of getting you onto that chronic headache,

579
00:21:48.630 --> 00:21:51.180
daily chronic headache, which we don't want.

580
00:21:51.180 --> 00:21:53.190
So what are these poor chronic daily headache people?

581
00:21:53.190 --> 00:21:56.370
15 or more headaches every month for three or more months.

582
00:21:56.370 --> 00:21:58.560
So this is a lotta, lotta headache.

583
00:21:58.560 --> 00:22:00.210
It doesn't matter what it started from.

584
00:22:00.210 --> 00:22:01.680
It might have started from a migraine,

585
00:22:01.680 --> 00:22:03.390
or it might have started from chronic tension.

586
00:22:03.390 --> 00:22:06.210
Once you get to chronic daily, it doesn't really matter.

587
00:22:06.210 --> 00:22:07.590
The treatment is the same.

588
00:22:07.590 --> 00:22:10.140
Stop all abortive therapy.

589
00:22:10.140 --> 00:22:11.850
This is actually personally the hardest thing

590
00:22:11.850 --> 00:22:14.100
I've ever tried to convince patients to do in the office.

591
00:22:14.100 --> 00:22:15.210
They don't want to give up.

592
00:22:15.210 --> 00:22:16.710
They're Motrin, they're Excedrin,

593
00:22:16.710 --> 00:22:18.270
they're triptans, whatever it is.

594
00:22:18.270 --> 00:22:20.580
'Cause they're like, "I'm gonna be hurting all the time."

595
00:22:20.580 --> 00:22:22.050
So this takes a lot of education

596
00:22:22.050 --> 00:22:23.880
to help them get through this.

597
00:22:23.880 --> 00:22:25.440
Pharmacologic treatment is gonna be

598
00:22:25.440 --> 00:22:26.801
so important for prevention.

599
00:22:26.801 --> 00:22:28.620
And topiramate and valproic acid

600
00:22:28.620 --> 00:22:30.630
are your strength of recommendation A.

601
00:22:30.630 --> 00:22:33.840
So I always start there unless there's a reason I can't.

602
00:22:33.840 --> 00:22:35.640
Second line would be your amitriptyline,

603
00:22:35.640 --> 00:22:37.920
gabapentin and tizanidine.

604
00:22:37.920 --> 00:22:40.830
SSRIs, Botox, propanolol,

605
00:22:40.830 --> 00:22:43.020
that might be helpful for migraine prevention,

606
00:22:43.020 --> 00:22:46.500
but has no helpfulness in chronic daily headache.

607
00:22:46.500 --> 00:22:50.070
So again, Topamax and valproic are gonna be your best bet.

608
00:22:50.070 --> 00:22:52.500
There is some recommendation for CBT.

609
00:22:52.500 --> 00:22:54.240
That's another thing that kinda if it shows up

610
00:22:54.240 --> 00:22:57.090
on the boards, most of the time CBT is the right answer.

611
00:22:57.090 --> 00:22:58.920
And biofeedback and relaxation

612
00:22:58.920 --> 00:23:01.650
also strength of the recommendation B if you have patients

613
00:23:01.650 --> 00:23:04.100
who are really not interested in pharmacotherapy.

614
00:23:05.400 --> 00:23:08.220
Cluster headaches was the person in our example here, right?

615
00:23:08.220 --> 00:23:11.220
So we see this not very commonly, less than 1% of time.

616
00:23:11.220 --> 00:23:13.470
But there is a male to female predominance

617
00:23:13.470 --> 00:23:15.870
of a two to three to one ratio.

618
00:23:15.870 --> 00:23:17.730
This is unilateral orbital,

619
00:23:17.730 --> 00:23:19.860
and they're kind of leaking on the same side

620
00:23:19.860 --> 00:23:20.693
as their headache.

621
00:23:20.693 --> 00:23:22.470
Their nose is running, their eye is running,

622
00:23:22.470 --> 00:23:24.660
they're just all over the place.

623
00:23:24.660 --> 00:23:25.590
Triggers listed here.

624
00:23:25.590 --> 00:23:28.140
Alcohol, nitroglycerin, nitrates in foods.

625
00:23:28.140 --> 00:23:30.540
So very processed foods is a really common trigger

626
00:23:30.540 --> 00:23:31.650
for our country.

627
00:23:31.650 --> 00:23:33.330
Strong odors.

628
00:23:33.330 --> 00:23:34.800
When you look at acute treatment,

629
00:23:34.800 --> 00:23:38.640
the oxygen and sub-Q or intranasal triptans

630
00:23:38.640 --> 00:23:41.580
have the best data, strength of recommendation A.

631
00:23:41.580 --> 00:23:44.340
Second line, somatostatin receptor agonist,

632
00:23:44.340 --> 00:23:46.470
that just recently got into the list.

633
00:23:46.470 --> 00:23:48.870
Nasal lidocaine also a new addition

634
00:23:48.870 --> 00:23:51.030
to the headache protocol there.

635
00:23:51.030 --> 00:23:53.340
But again, those are second line.

636
00:23:53.340 --> 00:23:55.860
They also talk a little bit about transitional therapy.

637
00:23:55.860 --> 00:23:57.000
If you have the ability

638
00:23:57.000 --> 00:23:59.640
or have someone in your kinda circle of colleagues

639
00:23:59.640 --> 00:24:03.330
who has the ability to do suboccipital steroid injections,

640
00:24:03.330 --> 00:24:05.130
they do really well as they're waiting

641
00:24:05.130 --> 00:24:06.690
for these other preventative medicines

642
00:24:06.690 --> 00:24:07.710
to get up in their system.

643
00:24:07.710 --> 00:24:09.330
Otherwise, they tend to be recurring

644
00:24:09.330 --> 00:24:11.103
and coming back to the ER a lot.

645
00:24:12.060 --> 00:24:14.220
Treatment of choice far and away is verapamil.

646
00:24:14.220 --> 00:24:15.660
But it's a big honkin' dose.

647
00:24:15.660 --> 00:24:18.210
You see that 240 to 320 is the dose

648
00:24:18.210 --> 00:24:19.710
that's most effective for patients.

649
00:24:19.710 --> 00:24:22.500
So sometimes people simply won't have enough blood pressure

650
00:24:22.500 --> 00:24:23.333
to be on that.

651
00:24:23.333 --> 00:24:26.520
If not, you'll see some of these second line agents up here.

652
00:24:26.520 --> 00:24:28.710
Topamax tends to be what most of us go to.

653
00:24:28.710 --> 00:24:30.630
Interesting that melatonin was on this list.

654
00:24:30.630 --> 00:24:32.220
So, hmm, I would try that first.

655
00:24:32.220 --> 00:24:34.470
It's cheap and pretty low risk.

656
00:24:34.470 --> 00:24:35.880
For refractory cases,

657
00:24:35.880 --> 00:24:37.830
we're seeing these gene-related,

658
00:24:37.830 --> 00:24:40.800
calcitonin gene-related peptide inhibitors coming into play,

659
00:24:40.800 --> 00:24:43.560
and we'll talk about that a little later with migraine.

660
00:24:43.560 --> 00:24:45.120
Deep brain stimulation, actually,

661
00:24:45.120 --> 00:24:48.543
for very refractory cases has very, very good effectiveness.

662
00:24:49.530 --> 00:24:51.090
Migraine's, much more common.

663
00:24:51.090 --> 00:24:52.290
We're gonna see this.

664
00:24:52.290 --> 00:24:55.470
About 25% of women, just under 10% of men

665
00:24:55.470 --> 00:24:57.240
will have these throughout their life.

666
00:24:57.240 --> 00:24:58.560
We don't know what's causing it.

667
00:24:58.560 --> 00:25:01.080
There's some genetic factor playing in there

668
00:25:01.080 --> 00:25:02.580
'cause there's a lot of family history of it,

669
00:25:02.580 --> 00:25:04.590
but we don't really understand it.

670
00:25:04.590 --> 00:25:08.313
There are these phases, the prodrome, the aura.

671
00:25:09.180 --> 00:25:10.800
We'll talk a little bit more about this aura,

672
00:25:10.800 --> 00:25:12.330
but oftentimes it's visual.

673
00:25:12.330 --> 00:25:14.880
This flickering lights is kind of the classic one.

674
00:25:14.880 --> 00:25:16.800
Shiny moving lights on one side,

675
00:25:16.800 --> 00:25:18.903
that's the scintillating scotoma.

676
00:25:19.800 --> 00:25:21.877
Then the headache comes, and then afterwards,

677
00:25:21.877 --> 00:25:24.390
"I'm totally fine as long as I don't move."

678
00:25:24.390 --> 00:25:27.060
But if I, like, bend over or move, the headache comes back.

679
00:25:27.060 --> 00:25:28.263
That's that postdrome.

680
00:25:29.580 --> 00:25:31.440
So migraine is a big deal.

681
00:25:31.440 --> 00:25:34.800
It's the sixth-leading cause of missed work in our country

682
00:25:34.800 --> 00:25:37.830
and counts for about $36 billion.

683
00:25:37.830 --> 00:25:39.894
Wow, that's a lot, with a B.

684
00:25:39.894 --> 00:25:42.210
So we need to make sure we're diagnosing it properly

685
00:25:42.210 --> 00:25:43.320
and getting people on treatment

686
00:25:43.320 --> 00:25:45.630
to really impact that disability.

687
00:25:45.630 --> 00:25:47.250
You have to have five different headaches

688
00:25:47.250 --> 00:25:49.260
before you call it migraine.

689
00:25:49.260 --> 00:25:51.480
It has to last between four and 72 hours.

690
00:25:51.480 --> 00:25:53.430
You need two of those top characteristics,

691
00:25:53.430 --> 00:25:56.550
unilateral, pulsitile, moderate or severe pain

692
00:25:56.550 --> 00:25:58.950
aggravated by physical activity

693
00:25:58.950 --> 00:26:00.930
and at least one of those next two,

694
00:26:00.930 --> 00:26:05.930
nausea and/or vomiting or photophobia and phonophobia.

695
00:26:05.970 --> 00:26:08.370
That's a change. That used to be an "or."

696
00:26:08.370 --> 00:26:11.130
So now to get that bottom point, you have to have both.

697
00:26:11.130 --> 00:26:13.350
If you don't have photophobia and phonophobia

698
00:26:13.350 --> 00:26:15.360
then you must have nausea, okay?

699
00:26:15.360 --> 00:26:18.210
They made it a little more strict for the criteria.

700
00:26:18.210 --> 00:26:19.590
And it can't be due to something else.

701
00:26:19.590 --> 00:26:21.210
If I have a big honkin' brain tumor,

702
00:26:21.210 --> 00:26:23.010
then I just have a headache from a brain tumor.

703
00:26:23.010 --> 00:26:24.633
I don't actually have migraines.

704
00:26:25.500 --> 00:26:27.090
What about migraine with aura.

705
00:26:27.090 --> 00:26:28.890
You have to have at least had two headaches

706
00:26:28.890 --> 00:26:30.990
that have the aura to call it.

707
00:26:30.990 --> 00:26:33.150
They have to be fully-reversible symptoms.

708
00:26:33.150 --> 00:26:34.890
And you see three of these things here.

709
00:26:34.890 --> 00:26:35.910
So kind of them.

710
00:26:35.910 --> 00:26:37.980
Aura comes on first, goes away,

711
00:26:37.980 --> 00:26:40.350
and then headache comes on within the hour.

712
00:26:40.350 --> 00:26:43.170
At least one of the aura symptoms must be positive

713
00:26:43.170 --> 00:26:44.880
for that point.

714
00:26:44.880 --> 00:26:47.760
So this is like, you know, like the scintillating scotoma.

715
00:26:47.760 --> 00:26:50.017
Whereas a negative symptom would mean,

716
00:26:50.017 --> 00:26:52.080
"I can't see or I can't hear."

717
00:26:52.080 --> 00:26:53.550
That'd be pretty troublesome.

718
00:26:53.550 --> 00:26:55.413
That's what a negative symptom is.

719
00:26:56.820 --> 00:26:58.500
So diagnosis here is clinical.

720
00:26:58.500 --> 00:27:00.360
There's not a lab test that's gonna show you.

721
00:27:00.360 --> 00:27:02.610
There's not an x-ray or CT that's gonna show you.

722
00:27:02.610 --> 00:27:04.530
So laboratory testing really limited

723
00:27:04.530 --> 00:27:06.210
but get a good history.

724
00:27:06.210 --> 00:27:08.160
They should have a normal neurologic exam.

725
00:27:08.160 --> 00:27:11.790
If they don't, you maybe have a different diagnosis.

726
00:27:11.790 --> 00:27:13.590
Neuroimaging is unnecessary.

727
00:27:13.590 --> 00:27:16.320
That's part of the radiology Choosing Wisely Campaign.

728
00:27:16.320 --> 00:27:17.880
So for the average migraine person,

729
00:27:17.880 --> 00:27:19.500
you do not need to image.

730
00:27:19.500 --> 00:27:21.330
You do not need an EEG.

731
00:27:21.330 --> 00:27:23.400
That's neurology choosing wisely campaign.

732
00:27:23.400 --> 00:27:25.950
It's not gonna add to your situation.

733
00:27:25.950 --> 00:27:27.780
These are red flags for neuroimaging, though.

734
00:27:27.780 --> 00:27:29.070
This is an important slide.

735
00:27:29.070 --> 00:27:30.960
Who needs neuroimage?

736
00:27:30.960 --> 00:27:32.827
Rapid increase in your headache frequency?

737
00:27:32.827 --> 00:27:34.410
"Like, I used to get migraines about,

738
00:27:34.410 --> 00:27:35.430
you know, three times a month,

739
00:27:35.430 --> 00:27:37.320
and now I'm getting 'em every day

740
00:27:37.320 --> 00:27:39.420
for, you know, the last six weeks."

741
00:27:39.420 --> 00:27:41.100
That's not normal.

742
00:27:41.100 --> 00:27:44.550
Loss of coordination, abnormal exam, papilledema on exam.

743
00:27:44.550 --> 00:27:47.070
I'm sure we're all doing dilated fundoscopic exams

744
00:27:47.070 --> 00:27:48.360
on these patients, right?

745
00:27:48.360 --> 00:27:49.470
No, we're not.

746
00:27:49.470 --> 00:27:51.060
But if they have visual symptoms,

747
00:27:51.060 --> 00:27:52.110
maybe take a look back there

748
00:27:52.110 --> 00:27:53.970
and see if that's what's goin' on.

749
00:27:53.970 --> 00:27:56.190
Migraine should not awaken you from sleep.

750
00:27:56.190 --> 00:27:57.780
You can awake with a migraine.

751
00:27:57.780 --> 00:27:59.880
But if it's bad enough to wake you up from sleep,

752
00:27:59.880 --> 00:28:01.740
you need to think about another headache etiology

753
00:28:01.740 --> 00:28:03.960
and think about neuroimaging.

754
00:28:03.960 --> 00:28:05.220
Worst headache of your life, right?

755
00:28:05.220 --> 00:28:07.110
That's a subarachnoid hemorrhage.

756
00:28:07.110 --> 00:28:08.760
If you have a patient with cancer,

757
00:28:08.760 --> 00:28:10.590
and they have headaches that are new,

758
00:28:10.590 --> 00:28:11.790
you have to look for mets.

759
00:28:11.790 --> 00:28:12.930
If they're an HIV patient,

760
00:28:12.930 --> 00:28:15.330
you wanna think about opportunistic infections.

761
00:28:15.330 --> 00:28:17.550
Lyme's disease, meningoencephalitis,

762
00:28:17.550 --> 00:28:19.800
all these things are gonna direct you.

763
00:28:19.800 --> 00:28:22.470
New onset of migraines over 50, very weird.

764
00:28:22.470 --> 00:28:23.610
Check that out.

765
00:28:23.610 --> 00:28:25.740
Rapid onset with strenuous exercise,

766
00:28:25.740 --> 00:28:27.210
that's our aneurysm, right?

767
00:28:27.210 --> 00:28:28.770
And what is the best test?

768
00:28:28.770 --> 00:28:29.760
No contrast.

769
00:28:29.760 --> 00:28:30.600
Okay, that's important.

770
00:28:30.600 --> 00:28:33.270
You can do a CT or MRI, but no contrast.

771
00:28:33.270 --> 00:28:37.080
Acute treatments, acetaminophen and NSAIDs and triptans.

772
00:28:37.080 --> 00:28:39.210
Watch out for some of these familial conditions

773
00:28:39.210 --> 00:28:42.870
or really uncontrolled hypertension that can be made worse.

774
00:28:42.870 --> 00:28:44.100
Second line agents would be,

775
00:28:44.100 --> 00:28:46.080
like, your metoclopramide, your Reglan.

776
00:28:46.080 --> 00:28:47.370
Pretty helpful there.

777
00:28:47.370 --> 00:28:49.860
They do have some risk of extrapyramidal side effects.

778
00:28:49.860 --> 00:28:50.693
Be aware of that.

779
00:28:50.693 --> 00:28:52.680
So not great for long-term use.

780
00:28:52.680 --> 00:28:54.960
Intranasal DHE, very helpful

781
00:28:54.960 --> 00:28:57.060
but lots of hypertension there.

782
00:28:57.060 --> 00:29:00.390
Opiates should be used very sparingly if at all.

783
00:29:00.390 --> 00:29:03.510
If they're very refractory and they end up in the hospital,

784
00:29:03.510 --> 00:29:07.740
IV DHE 45 is really great.

785
00:29:07.740 --> 00:29:09.180
It has a lot of puking, though.

786
00:29:09.180 --> 00:29:10.530
So you almost always have to have 'em on,

787
00:29:10.530 --> 00:29:13.590
like, a drip or something for all that nausea and vomiting.

788
00:29:13.590 --> 00:29:16.110
Mag sulfate, who knew it wasn't just for OB.

789
00:29:16.110 --> 00:29:18.810
You can also use this for refractory migraine.

790
00:29:18.810 --> 00:29:20.940
And if you have any of these treatments going on,

791
00:29:20.940 --> 00:29:23.400
you're oftentimes gonna do a steroid taper

792
00:29:23.400 --> 00:29:26.283
over 10 to 14 days so they don't rebound right away.

793
00:29:27.630 --> 00:29:28.560
Preventative treatment,

794
00:29:28.560 --> 00:29:31.050
less than one out of five people who qualify

795
00:29:31.050 --> 00:29:32.580
are getting preventative treatment.

796
00:29:32.580 --> 00:29:35.820
This is how you can change that disability index for them.

797
00:29:35.820 --> 00:29:37.380
So, "I'm having too many migraines.

798
00:29:37.380 --> 00:29:38.850
The medicines aren't working."

799
00:29:38.850 --> 00:29:40.080
Or, "I have one of these migraines

800
00:29:40.080 --> 00:29:41.010
that looks like a stroke."

801
00:29:41.010 --> 00:29:43.230
We don't want them in the ER getting CT'd all the time

802
00:29:43.230 --> 00:29:44.460
for a stroke eval.

803
00:29:44.460 --> 00:29:46.080
They need prevention.

804
00:29:46.080 --> 00:29:49.800
First line agents, this was a change in 2019.

805
00:29:49.800 --> 00:29:51.840
Amitriptyline has fallen off the list

806
00:29:51.840 --> 00:29:53.700
of first line down to second line,

807
00:29:53.700 --> 00:29:54.960
not because it doesn't work

808
00:29:54.960 --> 00:29:57.450
but because it has more side effects.

809
00:29:57.450 --> 00:29:59.880
So what are they listed as strength of recommendation A?

810
00:29:59.880 --> 00:30:02.670
Your valproic acid, frovatriptan.

811
00:30:02.670 --> 00:30:04.380
Wait, how can a triptan be prevention?

812
00:30:04.380 --> 00:30:06.150
Only for menstrual migraines.

813
00:30:06.150 --> 00:30:06.983
So you would start it,

814
00:30:06.983 --> 00:30:08.640
like, two days before your period starts

815
00:30:08.640 --> 00:30:11.550
and use it throughout the time of your menses.

816
00:30:11.550 --> 00:30:12.480
Propranolol has been on there for years.

817
00:30:12.480 --> 00:30:14.430
Timolol, metoprolol.

818
00:30:14.430 --> 00:30:17.190
Topiramate is one of the, literally, big stays for this.

819
00:30:17.190 --> 00:30:19.230
It's very, very effective.

820
00:30:19.230 --> 00:30:20.820
If no single agent is working,

821
00:30:20.820 --> 00:30:23.700
consider an alternative then go to a combination

822
00:30:23.700 --> 00:30:26.700
before going to a second line agent that you see here.

823
00:30:26.700 --> 00:30:27.870
Refractory cases,

824
00:30:27.870 --> 00:30:30.750
these are these calcitonin gene-related peptide meds.

825
00:30:30.750 --> 00:30:31.830
They're really effective.

826
00:30:31.830 --> 00:30:33.540
They're very expensive.

827
00:30:33.540 --> 00:30:35.640
I've listed the IV versions here.

828
00:30:35.640 --> 00:30:37.710
There is now an oral version, Nurtec,

829
00:30:37.710 --> 00:30:39.000
that some of you might be hearing about

830
00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:41.940
every other day use for prevention.

831
00:30:41.940 --> 00:30:43.140
These are hard to get covered,

832
00:30:43.140 --> 00:30:45.450
and oftentimes you'll have to engage with a neurologist,

833
00:30:45.450 --> 00:30:47.070
depending on the insurance in your area

834
00:30:47.070 --> 00:30:48.153
to get these covered.

835
00:30:49.110 --> 00:30:50.970
Neuromodulation has some good data.

836
00:30:50.970 --> 00:30:52.473
Botox has some good data.

837
00:30:53.340 --> 00:30:55.200
So what about this whole estrogen thing?

838
00:30:55.200 --> 00:30:57.817
We're not sure how consistent this link is.

839
00:30:57.817 --> 00:31:02.340
"Neurology" released a meta-analysis in 2017 of 15 studies.

840
00:31:02.340 --> 00:31:05.610
Seven of 'em showed no impact. The others did.

841
00:31:05.610 --> 00:31:08.340
The highest impact was like an odds ratio of seven

842
00:31:08.340 --> 00:31:11.130
if you've had migraine with aura and a smoker

843
00:31:11.130 --> 00:31:12.750
without causing a stroke.

844
00:31:12.750 --> 00:31:14.190
So even though the data's mixed,

845
00:31:14.190 --> 00:31:15.780
it was recently on an ITE,

846
00:31:15.780 --> 00:31:17.760
and I do counsel my patients about this.

847
00:31:17.760 --> 00:31:21.180
So if you've had migraine at all over the age of 35,

848
00:31:21.180 --> 00:31:23.010
I think estrogen's not for you.

849
00:31:23.010 --> 00:31:25.350
If you've had migraine with aura at any age,

850
00:31:25.350 --> 00:31:27.930
you need to think about non-estrogen.

851
00:31:27.930 --> 00:31:29.130
We have no time left.

852
00:31:29.130 --> 00:31:30.210
Multiple sclerosis,

853
00:31:30.210 --> 00:31:32.400
here's all I want you to know about this.

854
00:31:32.400 --> 00:31:34.140
It is very common in young people.

855
00:31:34.140 --> 00:31:36.000
The boards will have a young female, right?

856
00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:38.130
That's who's gonna be on there.

857
00:31:38.130 --> 00:31:39.900
There's lots of vague symptoms that it can be,

858
00:31:39.900 --> 00:31:41.550
but the questions they're gonna ask you about

859
00:31:41.550 --> 00:31:43.320
are optic neuritis.

860
00:31:43.320 --> 00:31:45.307
They're gonna ask you about that Lhermitte's sign.

861
00:31:45.307 --> 00:31:46.920
"A patient flexes their neck,

862
00:31:46.920 --> 00:31:49.440
and they have electric shocks down their arm."

863
00:31:49.440 --> 00:31:51.060
That's what the questions gonna say.

864
00:31:51.060 --> 00:31:54.120
Or, "They were feeling fine until they went to vacation

865
00:31:54.120 --> 00:31:55.080
at this hot spot,

866
00:31:55.080 --> 00:31:57.420
and they suddenly couldn't move part of their body."

867
00:31:57.420 --> 00:31:58.800
That's the Uhthoff's phenomenon.

868
00:31:58.800 --> 00:32:01.950
It gets worse when your body temperature goes up.

869
00:32:01.950 --> 00:32:03.900
Relapsing/remitting is the most common,

870
00:32:03.900 --> 00:32:06.810
which is great 'cause it's also the best prognosis.

871
00:32:06.810 --> 00:32:08.370
If you have an exacerbation,

872
00:32:08.370 --> 00:32:10.170
they get a crap ton of steroids.

873
00:32:10.170 --> 00:32:12.210
And it doesn't matter if you do an oral or IV.

874
00:32:12.210 --> 00:32:13.590
They both work about the same.

875
00:32:13.590 --> 00:32:14.970
But that's very important.

876
00:32:14.970 --> 00:32:19.230
If they're refractory to those IV steroids or oral steroids,

877
00:32:19.230 --> 00:32:20.733
then plasmapheresis.

878
00:32:21.630 --> 00:32:23.910
Tobacco cessation, we know it's great for everything.

879
00:32:23.910 --> 00:32:25.290
It's also good for MS.

880
00:32:25.290 --> 00:32:27.690
There's clear data now, strength of recommendation B,

881
00:32:27.690 --> 00:32:30.030
that says you will decrease disease progression

882
00:32:30.030 --> 00:32:32.220
by stopping smoking.

883
00:32:32.220 --> 00:32:35.010
Disease modifying agents should be started early.

884
00:32:35.010 --> 00:32:37.380
It does impact their relapse rate

885
00:32:37.380 --> 00:32:40.170
and decreased brain lesions on MRI.

886
00:32:40.170 --> 00:32:42.600
Immunomodulators is where we're at now

887
00:32:42.600 --> 00:32:45.120
because the immunosuppressives that we were using before

888
00:32:45.120 --> 00:32:46.803
have way too many side effects.

889
00:32:48.450 --> 00:32:49.890
Board frequent flyers right here.

890
00:32:49.890 --> 00:32:51.300
Put this in your study folder

891
00:32:51.300 --> 00:32:54.360
so you can be successful on the neuro part of the exam.

892
00:32:54.360 --> 00:32:55.193
Thank you so much.
(audience applauding)

893
00:32:55.193 --> 00:32:57.000
<v Host>Thank you very much, Dr. Holt.</v>

894
00:32:58.128 --> 00:33:00.795
(bright music)

